      "writtenOn": "2016-05-05T21:23:35Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I agree that we should choose between either returning SurfacePtr or Surface* here to clearly communicate intent. A reference to a shared_ptr looks very strange and as a consumer of the interface I would immediately wonder what is expected of me. Whereas if I get a shared_ptr I assume I\u0027m going to be able to hold on to it for as long as I like (barring the documentation saying otherwise) and if I get a Surface* I\u0027m going to assume that it will at most survive for as long as the object I\u0027m calling the method on (but I would like to see the documentation clarify this for me).\n\nThe biggest advantage of the reference solution as I see it is that it allows the consumer to choose what to do. If you assign the return value to a shared_ptr you will be able to hold on that and if you just want to call something on the surface right away you can do that without additional cost.\n\nIf we want to support both use-cases I would instead suggest that we have\nSurface* read() {}\nSurfacePtr readShared() {}\nSurface* draw() {}\nSurfacePtr drawShared() {}\n\nSo that the consumer will have to be more explicit and to make it more clear when reading the code.",
      "parentUuid": "ed5193a9_10d79435",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 46,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 46,
        "endChar": 53
      },
